==English==

===Etymology===
Derived from or popularized by [[w:Dion Boucicault|Dion Boucicault]]'s 1866 play ''Flying Scud'', in which a character removes himself from a difficult situation by saying "Excuse me, Mr. Quail, I can't stop: I've got to see a man about a dog". As a [[w:Prohibition|Prohibition]]-era reference to getting alcohol, influenced by the expression {{m|en|hair of the dog}}.

===Verb===
{{head|en|verb}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic|dated}} {{non-gloss definition|Used in place of a real explanation when excusing oneself for a short period of time, particularly {{lb|en|euphemism}} to use a toilet or {{lb|en|historical}} drink alcohol.}}
#: {{ux|en|I'll be right back, but I've got to go to the [[ladies' room]] to '''see a man about a dog'''.}}

====Usage notes====
Although almost any noun can be substituted in place of the {{m|en|dog}}, it now most commonly expressed as {{m|en|see a man about a horse}} with the implied context ''...about a'' {{m|en|bet}}.

